<body>
<h2>MA40042 Measure Theory and Integration</h2>



<p>This course is <strong><a href="http://www.bath.ac.uk/catalogues/2016-2017/ma/MA40042.html">MA40042</a> Measure theory and integration</strong>.</p>

<p>Lectures take place on:
<ul>
  <li> Tuesdays at 1415 in 3 West 4.7,
  <li> Thursdays at 1015 in 4 East 3.5.
  <li> Fridays at 1715 in Chancellor's Building 3.9.
</ul> </p>

<p>This year, the course will be split into two parts:
<ul>
  <li><strong>Measure theory</strong> is the first part of the course, will be lectured by <a href="..">me</a>, and will last about five weeks;
  <li><strong>Integration</strong> is the second part of the course, will be lectured by <a href="http://people.bath.ac.uk/mir20/">Dr Matt Roberts</a>, and will last about six weeks.
</ul> </p>

<p>This page is for the measure theory part of the course.</p>

<h3>Lecture notes</h3>

<p>I intend to provide printed notes for each lecture after the lecture has been delivered. They will be available online on <a href="https://moodle.bath.ac.uk/course/view.php?id=892">the course Moodle page</a>, on this webpage, and in hard copy in the following lecture.</p>

<p>This year, the course will be split into two parts:
<ul>
  <li><strong>Lecture 0:</strong> Introduction (<a href="ma40042-notes-00.pdf">Lecture notes</a>, Handout: <a href="ma40042-handout-00b.pdf">Conventions regarding infinity</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 1:</strong> <i>&sigma;</i>-algebras (<a href="ma40042-notes-01.pdf">Lecture notes</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 2:</strong> The Borel <i>&sigma;</i>-algebra (<a href="ma40042-notes-02.pdf">Lecture notes</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 3:</strong> Measures (<a href="ma40042-notes-03.pdf">Lecture notes</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 4:</strong> Constructing measures I: Outer measure (<a href="ma40042-notes-04.pdf">Lecture notes</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 5:</strong> Constructing measures II: Measurable sets (<a href="ma40042-notes-05.pdf">Lecture notes</a>, Handout: <a href="ma40042-handout-05.pdf">Carath&eacute;odory's splitting condition</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 6:</strong> Constructing measures III: Carath&eacute;odory's extension theorem (<a href="ma40042-notes-06.pdf">Lecture notes</a> <i><b>Warning:</b> Some typos in the proof of Lemma 6.9 that I haven't fixed yet</i>, Handout: <a href="ma40042-handout-06.pdf">Constructing measures: an outline</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 7:</strong> Proof of Carath&eacute;odory's extension theorem (<a href="ma40042-notes-07.pdf">Lecture notes</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 8:</strong> <i>&pi;</i>-systems, <i>&lambda;</i>-systems, and the uniqueness lemma (<a href="ma40042-notes-08.pdf">Lecture notes</a>, Handout: <a href="ma40042-handout-08.pdf">Set systems</a>)
  <li><strong>Lecture 9:</strong> More about the Lebesgue measure
</ul> </p>

<p>Lecture notes summarize the main theorems and definitions, but are not a substitute for attending lectures.</p>

<p>I very keen to hear about any errors &ndash; even small errors and typos &ndash; in the lecture notes. You can email them to me at <a href="mailto:m.aldridge@bath.ac.uk">m.aldridge@bath.ac.uk</a>.</p>


<h3>Problem sheets</h3>

<p>There will be one problem sheet per week. Students are expected to hand in their solutions to all problems by 1700 on the Monday of the following week to the MA40042 pigeonhole on the bottom floor of 4 West.</p>

<p>This year, the course will be split into two parts:
<ul>
  <li><strong><a href="ma40042-prob-1.pdf">Problem Sheet 1</a></strong> (due Monday 10 October)
  <li><strong><a href="ma40042-prob-2.pdf">Problem Sheet 2</a></strong> (due Monday 17 October) <a href="ma40042-sols-2.pdf">Solutions to  Question 3</a>
  <li><strong><a href="ma40042-prob-3.pdf">Problem Sheet 3</a></strong> (due Monday 24 October) <a href="ma40042-sols-3.pdf">Solutions to Questions 2 and 3</a>
  <li><strong><a href="ma40042-prob-4.pdf">Problem Sheet 4</a></strong> (due Wednesday 2 November)
</ul></p>

<p>The Tuesday lecture will be a problems class dedicated to going through the solutions to the problem sheet and answering other questions on the material.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.bath.ac.uk/library/exampapers/?code=MA40042">Past exam questions for the course</a> are available online.</p>

<h3>Books</h3>

<p>The lectures should cover all necessary material for the course. However, it may be helpful to consult a textbook for further information or a different view of the material.</p>

<p>I have found the following books useful:
<ul>
  <li>D Williams, <i>Probability with Martingales</i>, Cambridge University Press, 1991. [Chapters 1 and A1]
  <li>T Lindstr&oslash;m, <i>Mathematical Analysis</i>. <a href="http://www.uio.no/studier/emner/matnat/math/MAT2400/v14/">Available online</a> [Chapters 5 and 6]
</ul>
Williams takes a more probabilistic view of material, which some may prefer.</p>

<p>I haven't used them much myself, but hear good things about:
<ul>
  <li>P Billingsley, <i>Probability and Measure</i>, anniversary edition, Wiley, 2012. [Chapters 1 and 2]
  <li>R Durrett, <i>Probability: Theory and examples</i>, fourth edition, Cambridge University Press, 2010. [Chapter 1 and Appendix A]
  <li>W Rudin, <i>Real and Complex Analysis</i>, third edition,  McGraw-Hill, 1987. [Chapters 1 and 2]
</ul></p>

<p>All these books cover relevant material for the Integration part of the course also.</p>

<h3>Office hours</h3>

<p>There will not be a set time for office hours. You are welcome to <a href="mailto:m.aldridge@bath.ac.uk">email me</a> to arrange a meeting, or just try dropping into my office (4 West 5.5).



